  "text": "Node.js core implements comprehensive prototype pollution defenses across its JavaScript modules using multiple complementary strategies:\n\n## 1. Primordials-Based Protection (lib/internal/per_context/primordials.js)\n\nThe cornerstone of Node's defense is the primordials system, which creates safe, frozen wrappers of built-in objects to prevent prototype pollution attacks. Key components include:\n\n- **makeSafe()** function: Creates safe subclasses of built-in constructors (Map, Set, WeakMap, WeakSet, Promise, etc.) by freezing their prototypes and setting them to null via ObjectSetPrototypeOf(safe.prototype, null)\n- **Safe* Classes**: SafeMap, SafeSet, SafeWeakMap, SafeWeakSet, SafeArrayIterator, and Safe Promise variants that replace their unsafe counterparts throughout the codebase\n- **Object Definition**: Uses ReflectDefineProperty with `{ __proto__: null, ...desc }` pattern to safely define properties, preventing prototype chain attacks\n\n## 2. Null-Prototype Object Pattern\n\nNumerous core modules use `{ __proto__: null }` object literals for safe property storage:\n- lib/v8.js, lib/vm.js, lib/quic.js: Use null-prototype objects for constants and configuration\n- lib/_http_agent.js, lib/_http_outgoing.js: Safely store HTTP options with `{ __proto__: null, ...options }`\n- lib/internal/webidl.js, lib/internal/options.js: Safe dictionary creation with null prototypes\n- lib/internal/util/inspect.js, lib/internal/heap_utils.js, lib/internal/event_target.js: Property definitions with null prototypes\n\n## 3. ObjectPrototypeHasOwnProperty Pattern\n\nCore modules defensively use ObjectPrototypeHasOwnProperty for safe property checks:\n- lib/buffer.js, lib/cluster.js, lib/internal/tty.js: Check own properties to avoid inherited prototype properties\n- lib/child_process.js, lib/internal/errors.js: Validate object properties without triggering prototype lookups\n- lib/internal/util/inspect.js, lib/internal/validators.js: Safe property iteration and checking\n- lib/internal/crypto/util.js, lib/internal/crypto/webidl.js: Secure algorithm/parameter validation\n\n## 4. ObjectCreate(null) with Safe Properties\n\nFiles that create null-prototype objects with protected properties:\n- lib/quic.js: Uses ObjectCreate(null, { __proto__: null, ...properties })\n- lib/internal/error_serdes.js: Creates `const all = { __proto__: null }` for error property serialization\n- lib/internal/console/global.js: ReflectDefineProperty with null-prototype descriptors\n- lib/internal/worker/io.js: Safely creates property descriptors with null prototypes\n\n## 5. Prototype Chain Hardening with ObjectSetPrototypeOf\n\nCore modules set safe prototypes explicitly:\n- lib/net.js, lib/dgram.js: `ObjectSetPrototypeOf(Server.prototype, EventEmitter.prototype)`\n- lib/buffer.js: `ObjectSetPrototypeOf(Buffer, Uint8Array)`\n- lib/internal/per_context/domexception.js: `ObjectSetPrototypeOf(safe.prototype, null)`\n- lib/internal/freeze_intrinsics.js: Deep freezing of intrinsic objects to prevent prototype pollution\n\n## 6. ESLint Enforcement\n\ntools/eslint-rules/avoid-prototype-pollution.js enforces:\n- Null-prototype objects for property descriptors\n- Safe primordial usage patterns\n- Avoidance of unsafe built-in methods that lookup prototype properties\n- Proxy handler null-prototype requirement\n\n## 7. High-Level Module Protection\n\nCluster, worker, test runner, and stream modules universally use Safe* versions:\n- lib/internal/cluster/: Uses SafeMap, SafeSet for handle and worker tracking\n- lib/internal/test_runner/: SafeMap for test assertions, SafeSet for tracking\n- lib/internal/streams/: ObjectSetPrototypeOf patterns for stream hierarchy\n- lib/internal/perf/: SafeMap for performance metrics and user timing\n\nThis multi-layered approach ensures that user-controlled input cannot pollute the prototype chain of critical system objects, protecting against both direct and indirect prototype pollution attacks throughout Node.js core."
}

